      <p class="montserrat">
        Lev N. Tolstoy's "What Man Lives For" is a story that deals with deep
        philosophical and moral questions about what human beings live for in
        life. In this story, Tolstoy argues that man lives by love, benevolence
        and faith in God. At the end of the story, the Angel who lives in
        Simon's house teaches him three important truths: that man cannot live
        without love, that the person who lives for himself is the one who
        suffers the most, and that people can survive only through love. These
        teachings reflect Tolstoy's thoughts on human nature and morality. Simon
        and his wife Matryona learn important lessons about humanity and love by
        accepting the helpless stranger (the Angel).
      </p>
